WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
 Hello and welcome to my lecture where I share my thoughts on the use of artificial intelligence in programming classes.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:13.000
 My name is Charles Severance and I'm a professor at the University of Michigan School of Information in Ann Arbor, Michigan.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:20.000
 So you may know me from some of my online classes, Python for Everybody, 3 Million Students, the largest programming class in the world,

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.000
 Django for Everybody, C Programming for Everybody.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:32.000
 I'm building a series of curriculums, a series of courses that lead towards what I call a master programmer,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:43.000
 which is a way to get people to become very skilled programmers in shorter time by giving the essential foundations of programming rather than a four-year degree.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.000
 So it's much less than a four-year degree. That's my goal right now is to make programmers faster and better.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
 So the goals of this presentation are not to make policy for my course or any other course.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.000
 Policies really depend on the course and the goals of the course and the course material and the instructor.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:07.000
 So don't use this as like telling your teacher that somehow they should change their policies because of Dr. Chuck's talk.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:12.000
 These are just my experiences and opinions and ways I've learned things over time and my theories

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:22.000
 and how I try to explain to my students about the good and the bad about using AI when working in a program, taking a programming class.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.000
 So to AI or not to AI, that is the question. Well, I think the answer is you have to use it.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
 From now on, AI is part of software development. You can't deny that.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
 You're not going to get a job if you say, well, I don't use AI. Well, you better use it.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
 I want you to learn how to use it to make you a better programmer, not how to not make you a better programmer.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:53.000
 They're like, oh, AI is good enough. And any AI technique that I teach or anyone else teaches is going to be out of date so quickly.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
 Everything is changing. Every couple of months, things get better.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:04.000
 Sometimes I'm using a piece of AI and it's stuck on something and I'll set it aside and come back in another month and the models will change.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:09.000
 And I'll like, what about that? And it's like, oh, yeah, I'll fix that for you. Like, oh, great.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:19.000
 But one thing I think is permanent forever, the better you understand programming and the foundations of programming, the better you're going to be at using AI to help you develop software.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:27.000
 The dangers of AI is that using AI does not mean that you don't need to learn anything in a programming class or in a job.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:35.000
 Believe me, if the only thing you can do is do what AI does for you, then you're probably not going to get a very good job.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:44.000
 And if you're taking a class, you become a better programmer, but then you rely on AI to actually not study the class material and not learn the class material.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:53.000
 And the first and then the first part of the course, it's particularly perilous because then you you just wasted all your time and money, took a course and I didn't learn anything.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
 And AI caused you to not learn anything. My thinking on this has evolved over time.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:05.000
 We first heard about AI like I was in the middle of teaching winter semester, twenty, twenty three.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:15.000
 We had a quick, quick faculty meeting. We pretty much all without without even coordinating, we just knew that we weren't going to prohibit AI in programming classes.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
 We wanted to find a way to teach with AI and we wanted to find a way to use AI wisely.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:26.000
 So for about a year, year and a half, I kind of adjusted my class.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
 More paper stuff, et cetera, et cetera.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:38.000
 And it had mixed results. The thing I didn't like about it was and this is true going back over a decade.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:46.000
 Every time I build something that tries to force students to do something my way rather than the easiest way for them,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:53.000
 I harm the students who want to learn and I don't really stop the students who don't want to learn from taking the easy way out.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:59.000
 So really from last semester onward, I'm just treating AI like Stack Overflow.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
 I'm not uniquely thinking about it, not doing anything to help it, not do anything to stop it.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:14.000
 As a teacher, you might think it's great to go to college and snap your fingers and get A's in all your classes.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:21.000
 And in one day you get a degree and you graduate and you want to get a great job.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.000
 Unfortunately, when you go to school, you're supposed to learn something.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
 So I'm a teacher and I'm part of your schooling.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:39.000
 So I feel that my job is to take some set of materials, maybe programming language, and change how you know about it.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.000
 Right. You don't know something before and you do know something after.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:50.000
 And I got 15 weeks to do that. And believe me, I don't want to waste your time. I really don't.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:59.000
 If I could grab a little USB thing and plug it into the back of your neck like they did in the Matrix and teach you something,

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.000
 I would invent that and I would do that.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.000
 The human mind just does not accept new knowledge that fast.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:13.000
 And so we have to come up with a way. And we only have 15 weeks or 10 weeks or whatever.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
 So we have a short period of time and a lot of material to cover.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:23.000
 So how do we take a lot of material and cover it in a short period of time?

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:30.000
 And the answer is you break it into small, doable chunks.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:34.000
 The education word for this is the zone of proximal development.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:44.000
 And that is the way you learn is someone like me with an assignment or whatever pushes you outside your comfort zone just a little bit.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
 And then we hang out with you and help you through that and then you learn something.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:53.000
 And then a week later, you got a new comfort zone. We push you just a little bit out of that comfort zone.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:00.000
 So we're keeping you under a little bit of stress each week that hopefully you're adding some stuff up and you're retaining it.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
 So some teachers teach too much in a week and then you don't retain it.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:11.000
 I try to figure out how much I can teach you in one week that you will retain so your knowledge builds.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.000
 Naturally, what you find is in the beginning of classes,

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:20.000
 the amount that I can teach you in a week is smaller than what I can in later, right?

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:27.000
 Because in the later classes, I can assume that you'd remember most of the stuff that I've already taught you in earlier classes.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.000
 And this is just natural. It's how you build classes.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:38.000
 The problem is, is these simple early assignments are much easier for you to complete.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
 And so students who are tired, who are busy, who just came off of a summer vacation,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
 they're like, well, I don't really want to work hard this week. I'm going to work twice as hard next week.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.000
 So I'm going to have AI do the homework this week. Yay.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.000
 So they do that and they're like, whew, I got 100% and AI did it.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:03.000
 And then they promise that the second week they'll work twice as hard, learn everything in the first week and everything in the second week.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
 And they're like, oh, wow, I wonder if AI could do this second week homework.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
 And then they do have AI do the second week homework.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:17.000
 And they keep doing this, not because they're bad. Students are bad. I mean, students are mostly tired.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
 School is hard, especially when you're taking a course that has a schedule

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
 and a teacher like me that's telling you what to do every week.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
 When I finally graduated with my PhD, someone asked me, do you miss school?

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
 I said, I don't want any more deadlines. I don't want to be told to do any homework on a time.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:40.000
 Learning's fun, but having deadlines isn't. Unfortunately, those two things are connected.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
 If you're not forced to do something, you will delay it.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:50.000
 So here's the problem. Let's just say weeks one through five in this particular course are tractable for AI.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.000
 And AI is not really learning anything. AI is no smarter at week five than it was at week one.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
 OK, you're not teaching AI anything as you're going through this.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
 If you went through it, you'd be learning something.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:07.000
 But AI is already smarter than you and smarter than whatever.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:16.000
 So the problem is, is that you get to week six and for whatever reason, AI can't solve your problem.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:22.000
 So then what you're forced to do in week six is you're really forced to either drop the class

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:27.000
 or you have to learn six weeks of material in one week.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:32.000
 And you've been tired and busy and you've got other classes and it doesn't happen.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:39.000
 And seven days later, the class is going to take another step. Seven more days, class taking another step.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:44.000
 And this is part of the class where the class is starting to speed up. We call it the knee of the curve.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:49.000
 So you picked the exact wrong time to not know what was going on in this class.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:56.000
 Usually you have to drop the class or get a very low grade in the class because about the one third to one half point

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:03.000
 is the place in most classes where programming classes where AI just can't do it.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
 Before AI, I always made my assessments real work.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
 So writing Django applications is the learning objective of the course.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
 Then I want my assignments to be writing Django applications.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:18.000
 And so the key thing there is if I want you to know how to do something and then use AI to do it,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
 but you actually learn how to do it and AI makes it better for you.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:26.000
 Great. I just taught you how to use AI to solve the learning objective of my course,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
 which you will then be able to do when you get in your job.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
 So my assignments integrate across many sources.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:36.000
 I mentioned I don't give you a little single paragraph that completely describes it and then grade that.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
 No, you got to look at sample code. You got to look at some code walkthroughs and demos.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
 I'm explaining concepts, right?

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
 So then what you got to do is you got to learn the concepts and then you got to pull from places

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
 and you got to synthesize all that together.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.000
 And so the problem is, is that AI just wants to look at a few paragraphs

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
 and then write some code because it can't do that.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:03.000
 Like, let's write a database application to store and retrieve autos and auto data.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:08.000
 Well, that's not what my assignments are. My assignments are look at this code, adapt it,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
 look at that code, adapt it, look at this, read this thing, adapt it, watch this lecture,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
 adapt all that stuff together and synthesize it together and then build a piece of software,

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:22.000
 not just to solve the problem, but to solve the problem using the techniques that you saw

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
 in all the stuff that was in the class.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
 Now, that doesn't mean that you can't give AI enough context.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:36.000
 If you were really organized and you figured out every single asset that was in the course this week

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:41.000
 and you could somehow feed it into AI and build AI's understanding up and said, OK,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:49.000
 now using the stuff I just gave you, write an auto tracking, automobile tracking application.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:54.000
 You might get it. It might. It's not dumb. It might.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:00.000
 And if you are smart enough to give it enough context to solve one of my assignments,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
 I actually kind of gained some respect for you.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:08.000
 And my teaching assistants will sit down in a meeting and tell me, oh, yeah, I feed it all into AI.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
 I've got these 14 things in AI and I tell it to write the code.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
 They probably fed the sample solution in as well.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:18.000
 And so, yeah, the AI is pretty smart at that point.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:23.000
 So my autograders for the software look for specific techniques, not just any old technique,

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:27.000
 but the specific techniques from the material, my course materials in your solution.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
 You can't just take and argue with me.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:33.000
 It says you told me to write an automobile database and I wrote an automobile database.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.000
 Too bad it didn't pass the autograder.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
 Another technique I have is cumulative exams.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:46.000
 So like in week 1, 2, 3, and 4, in order to discourage you from just using AI, I say there'll be a midterm.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:50.000
 And that midterm will be cumulative.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:58.000
 And so if you take weeks 1 through 5 plus a little bit and you think you can do that in one week with AI, great.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
 Good luck with you. The exams are going to be more difficult.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
 They are going to be potentially as difficult as weeks 1 through 5 combined.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
 And if you know everything in week 1 through 5, they're pretty easy.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
 But if you don't, you're not going to do it.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
 And so I generally use about half or a little under half of my scores.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:22.000
 Grades are calculated based on exams.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:28.000
 And so if you get 100% on the assignments and you don't do well on the exams, you kind of have a 50% in the class.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:36.000
 And so that's another motivation to not just depend on AI because AI won't be able to do the exam for you.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
 And so, I mean, I do let people do some exams online,

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:45.000
 but sometimes they're just so big that AI can't get it right and the autograders, like I said, are too specific.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
 So here's my recommendations.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
 Don't just rush to the assignments and just smash them out with AI.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
 I understand you're tired and you don't have enough time.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.000
 The problem is, is that that strategy will initially lead off into success,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.000
 but that will reinforce your bad choice of not studying, right?

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
 If you skim the material before and at least while you're working and if AI is helping you,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
 maybe some pieces will stick in your mind as you're going through.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.000
 And don't be so impatient in the first few weeks.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
 The first few weeks are the easy part of the class on purpose.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
 So if you don't give yourself a chance to learn in the easy part of the class,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:23.000
 you're not going to learn in the hard part of the class.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:30.000
 Now, if you already know the material because that's the easy class for you.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
 Great. You'll be using AI. You know how to use AI.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
 You could do it in your sleep. So that's not the student I'm talking to.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
 I'm talking about the student that's actually learning this material.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:46.000
 And again, the key is a programming course designed to stretch you and teach you a little bit more every week

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.000
 so that when you're done, you can do something big.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
 AI is great and getting better.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
 This is a circuit layout tool that I'm building for a course,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:01.000
 an upcoming course I'm going to teach called Computer Architecture for Everybody.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
 Hardware, how chips are made.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:11.000
 This is based on a piece of software that I learned in grad school like 25 plus years ago called Magic.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
 It came from a university in California, Berkeley.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:18.000
 That's why it's called Mystic because it's like my own version of Magic.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:25.000
 This does circuit layout. All those layers are polysilicon, n-dope, silicon, p-dope, silicon, metal.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.000
 You don't need to know this. It's not a hardware class.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:32.000
 And literally, I just talked AI through building all this.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.000
 This is only a couple hundred lines of code.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:42.000
 And it's a reasonable facsimile of this semi-professional software called Magic.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
 And the only part that I really helped in was the circuit simulation

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:51.000
 because maybe the AI will figure that out too eventually.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:57.000
 But I used some recursion and some other tricks to make the little pluses and minuses go.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
 But I've been doing these kinds of small tasks with AI for a while.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:06.000
 And I'll just say, I'm really starting to believe.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:14.000
 I'm starting to believe that AI is more of a partner than like barely capable of doing the simplest things.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:18.000
 And as I increasingly trust and believe in AI as my partner,

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:22.000
 I'm starting to communicate with it as if it's more intelligent.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:28.000
 So my conversations with AI are longer, more jargon-loaded,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:32.000
 as if I was talking to someone who is almost as good as me.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:39.000
 And I will say that as I increase the sophistication with which I communicate with AI,

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:42.000
 I am getting better results from AI.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:48.000
 And so this goes back to if you're good at programming and you're good at understanding problems,

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:53.000
 then your communication with AI can be at a much higher level with much more detail

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
 and you will get better results.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
 So thanks for listening.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:05.000
 I hope to see you in class or online, perhaps in the Ann Arbor campus or perhaps in an online venue.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
 Cheers.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.920
 (jazz piano music)

